author: @adamd9166
text: Maybe a bit nit-picky on my part, but it drives me CRAZY when recruiters/hiring managers cannot post the job ad properly.  Big things are: spelling mistakes on basic words ("Bachalors"), inconsistent details (hiring for junior, yet listing mid-senior) and above all, NOT knowing what a Data Analyst does.  They hold applicants to a very high standard, yet cannot bother to proof-read their own job ad.  It drives me absolutely bonkers!

author: @stevemcclure2879
text: Back when I lived in DC doing contract work a security clearance was a highly valued and prized credential.  Back then they were hard to come by and get.  I had heard through the grape vine that a lot of former military people with these credentials didn't realize how much they could command and were routinely underpaid.  I'm curious if that is sill the case and why you see ridiculous job ads like you posted.  I also work in the Salesforce space, anything with one or more certifications usually start around $80K.  I'm a little confused about "Beets" and "Beats" but wanted to include both to be safe :)

author: @alextreynker9698
text: Here are my two cents on this, this entire situation is completely ridicules! and I think companies and HR specifically is going to create a nightmare of scenario in 1 - 2 years time because they will need to rehire so many people and fast... and it will cost a lot of money to the companies.  People who are senior and have no other choice but to take these positions will be unhappy. They will feel that their were screwed over by companies who took advantage of the pandemic, and in turn will be the first to jump ship when the recovery will start. I assume recovery, specifically in the Data Analytics world will have a lot of demand as companies will need to process insane amount of data and fast. So instead of having a junior employee that will be with his natural career progression for about 2 - 4 years... employers will get unhappy staff that will change jobs in a heart beat for more money, again I assume would be around 6 - 12 months for good senior analysts. I backup my assumption by vaccines success rate and overall stock exchange recovery.   ***disclaimer - I'm currently finishing my data analyst courses (SQL, Excel, Python and Power BI) and trying to make a career change during all of this pandemic. 41 days to this wonderful year to go! whoohooo.... begone already! 😅

author: @KaipovTim
text: I think, the majority of those vacancies are never ment to actually hire anyone in the first place. I don't know about US, but vacancies of Russian government (militilary including) are often just official fiction - the actual employee is already chosen, but they have to put up a show (because of the laws) "we actualy tried to find someone else". So what we see - is vacancy with rediculous requirements. As for consulting companies - the hiring process itself is big part of their marketing strategy. So such vacancies' purpose is to create the reputation "God, thier Junior level is so high, the Seniors must be Gods alive", not only in the eyes of general public, but of their clients in particular. Beets=)
